tags.description: Lookout tower to monitor for rough bar conditions, see NOAA Coast Pilot 10, (1st ed. 2020) Chapter 4, paragraph 80.
tags.name: Grays Harbor Bar Lookout Tower
tags.operator: U.S. Coast Guard - Station Grays Harbor

tags.description: Built in 1998 to house the magnificent Destruction Island Lens.  Specific design criteria had to be met in the construction of this building, which holds the exhibit.
tags.name: Destruction Island Lens Exhibit Hall

tags.description: McCausland Hall, which was used as an equipment and service building by the Coast Guard, has been converted into a lecture/events hall for museum programs.  This building is available for rent for meetings, wedding receptions, and other activities.
tags.name: McCausland Hall
tags.note: Listed in Washington Registry and Eligible for listing on National Register of Historic Places

tags.description: Built in 1939. The original building was designed to traditional Nantucket-Coast Guard Architecture Standards and sits within a five-building complex in the Marina District of Westport.
tags.name: Historic Coast Guard Station
tags.note: Listed in Washington Registry and Eligible for listing on National Register of Historic Places

tags.description: U.S. Coast Guard Boat Station, primary duties, include search and rescue, enforcement of laws and treaties, National Defense, marine environmental protection and recreational boating safety. Area of responsibility from Queets River to Ocean Park, WA.
tags.name: U.S. Coast Guard Station

tags.description: The workhorse of the Heavy Weather Fleet, the Coast Guard 47-foot Motor Lifeboat is self-righting and self-bailing. A fast response boat for rescue operations in the most extreme weather conditions like breaking surf and high seas.
tags.name: Grays Harbor Station Boathouse

tags.description: Buildings constructed to house the marine mammal exhibit including a minke and gray whale.
tags.name: Whale House
